A yearly subscription is refundable within 14 days of purchase and includes a 365-day membership. This strengthening followed Statistics SA saying the country’s GDP declined 6% year-on-year in the third quarter of 2020. This decline was smaller than the expected 7% year-on-year drop. Read: Third quarter GDP increases by an annualised 66.1% The rise against the dollar was also mirrored against the currencies of South Africa’s other leading trading partners. It was up 0.95% to R18.18 against the euro and 1.09% 20.06 against the pound. The rise in the value of the rand against the dollar has seen it go from R15.48 on November 30. Though the rand has showed renewed strength, it is still way off from where it started the year. On January 2 it was trading at R14.09 to the dollar. It sank to R19.03 on April 24 at the height of the hard national Covid-19 lockdown.